ons. Its products and services include iPhone, iPad, iPod, Mac, iPod, Apple TV, a portfolio of consumer and professional software applications, the iOS and OS X operating systems, iCloud, and accessories, service and support offerings.  The company also sells and delivers digital content and applications through the iTunes Store, App Store, iBooks Store, and Mac App Store. It sells its products worldwide through its retail stores, online stores, and direct sales force and third-party cellular network carriers, wholesalers, retailers, and value-added resellers to the consumer and also sells third-party iPhone, iPad, Mac and iPod compatible products, including application software, and accessories, through its online and retail stores. The company was founded by Steven Paul Jobs, Steve Wozniak and Ronald Gerald Wayne on April 1, 1976 and is headquartered in Cupertino, CA.  [...] more\n									 \n\n								\n		\n			More on Forbes\n\n\n	\n				\n					\n\n	\n		\n		 VIP Orbit Reinvents Itself As Vipor CRM\n		\n			\nOne of the most important functions of a computer or mobile device, for many people, is managing contacts. More than just maintaining a database of names, email addresses, and phone numbers, though, contact management is about managing relationships. VIP Orbit has been my tool of choice for a few years now, but now it’s been replaced by read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Tony Bradley, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n		\n		 If The Minimum Wage Doesn''t Benefit The Poor Then What''s The Point Of Having The Minimum Wage?\n		\n			\nIt’s not often that I agree with the New York Times on matters economic and it might be all the way back in 1987 that I last agreed with it on the subject of the minimum wage. But miracles do happen and so has one here. The NYT was once right on the subject of that minimum wage. They both argued that sure, we want to increase the incomes of the read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Tim Worstall, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n			\n	\n	\n			\n				\n					\n				\n			\n	\n		\n			New Samsung Galaxy S6 Details Will Anger Apple\n		\n			\niOS. That’s what most iPhone and iPad owners cite when they explain why they bought their device. Being part of ’s ecosystem is a massive draw for many, but for Apple’s future Touch ID and its intrinsic role in security and finance offers a bigger differentiator than the subjective arguments about&nbsp;iOS vs Android. And now Samsung is going to read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Gordon Kelly, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					undefined\n					undefined\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n	\n		\n				 		Galaxy Note 4 vs iPhone 6 Plus\n			\n\n			\n\n		\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n		\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Gordon Kelly, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n		\n		 Xiaomi''s Not Really In The Same Business As Apple Let Alone The Same Conversation\n		\n			\nA nice little piece over at Fortune talking about how Xiaomi is trying to place itself as being in direct competition with Apple for that top end of the smartphone market. And while we definitely get a sense that that’s how the company is trying to position itself that’s not how it appears when we drill down into the economic reality of the two read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Tim Worstall, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n			\n	\n	\n			\n				\n					\n				\n			\n	\n		\n			Top 6 Essential Android And iOS Apps From This Week\n		\n			\nIt’s time for this week’s Android and iOS app round-up. As usual, the apps included will be a combination of the best of what has been released this week, but also my favourite must-have apps that I’ve recently come across. \nIf you’ve got an app suggestion, or, if you’re a developer and want me to test your app out. Feel free to message read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Jay McGregor, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n	\n		\n				 		Best Apps For Holiday Shoppers\n			\n\n			\n\n		\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n		\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Jay McGregor, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n		\n		 8 Successful Products That Only Exist Because of Failure\n		\n			\nFailure is a part of almost everyone’s journey. Founders, inventors, great athletes, it doesn’t matter – everyone’s success is built on a previous failure. Even I’ve failed -multiple times – but I’ve never let it stop me. Here are eight successful products that only exist because someone failed – and dared to keep going. \nWD-40 read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Sujan Patel, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n				\n					\n						\n					\n				\n		\n		 Kevin Knopp Brings Mass Spectrometry To The Masses\n		\n			\nA Series of Forbes Insights Profiles of Thought Leaders Changing the Business Landscape. \nKevin Knopp asked the questions others hadn’t thought of and along the way started a company with a “dream team” of co-founders&nbsp;to put mass spectrometry on a mini scale. \nWhat if a small, laptop-sized device could help read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Bruce Rogers, Forbes Staff\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n				\n					\n						\n					\n				\n		\n		 iPod Creator Tony Fadell Hints At Larger Google Hardware Role As He Takes Over Glass\n		\n			\nBy Aaron Tilley and Ryan Mac \nEver since Google acquired smart home gadget maker Nest for $3.2 billion in January 2014, rumors that Nest’s cofounder, Tony Fadell, would eventually take over Google’s hardware future have bubbled up. We may be seeing the beginnings of that transition right now. \nFadell, an Apple alum read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Aaron Tilley, Forbes Staff\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n				\n					\n						\n					\n				\n		\n		 Trunx Attempts To Gain A Cloud Storage Advantage Through Price. Nice Idea But Doomed To Failure\n		\n			\nThere are dozens of vendors all trying to compete in the file storage and synchronization space&nbsp;– soon to be public Box, rumored to be going public Dropbox. Large platform vendors Apple, Citrix, Amazon, Microsoft and Google and “pure play” storage vendors Egnyte, Accellion and OxygenCloud to name but a few. With so much action in the space, read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Ben Kepes, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n				\n					\n						\n					\n				\n		\n		 More Vertical Analytics Solutions--INETCO Goes Analytical On ATM Data\n		\n			\nI’m seeing more examples of big data and analytics vendors tailoring their offerings to specific verticals. At the same time we’re seeing specialist vertical vendors add an analytics solution on top of their existing offerings. It makes sense, partly because individual verticals have highly specific needs that can’t be met by plain vanilla read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Ben Kepes, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n			\n	\n	\n			\n				\n					\n				\n			\n	\n		\n			6 Powerful Smartphones For Under $400\n		\n			\nThe affordable smartphone is a trend that’s quietly brewing as the perfect storm of factors form; cheaper materials and a voracious interest from developing markets. The success of companies like Xiaomi are the reason why major players like are steering their gaze toward the low-end like they’ve just seen oil spluttering&nbsp;out of the read &raquo;\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Jay McGregor, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n				\n				\n					\n\n	\n	\n		\n				 		The Richest In Tech On The 2014 Forbes 400\n			\n\n			\n\n		\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n				\n					\n				\n		\n		\n				\n					\n				\n			\n				Jay McGregor, Contributor\n			\n		\n	\n					\n		